Analysis

Let’s start observing the correlation between variables. The variables considered are as follows: • Suicide index: Suicide rate per 100,000 inhabitants (main dependent variable). • Time period: Year of observation (2005–2020). • Region: Identifier of the Italian region, representing the spatial unit of analysis. • GDP per capita: Gross Domestic Product per capita, expressed in euros at constant prices. • Employment percentage: Employment rate of the population aged 15–65. • Risk of poverty: Poverty risk rate, defined as the percentage of the population with income below the relative poverty threshold. • Inequality 80-20: 80/20 income ratio, an indicator of economic inequality between the highest and lowest income groups. • Neet rate: Share of young people classified as NEET (Not in Education, Employment, or Training), expressed as a percentage. • University graduates: Percentage of the population holding a university degree, used as a proxy for human capital. • Fertility region rate: Regional fertility rate (average number of children per woman). • Gender gap index: Index of gender disparity calculated by Eurostat, measuring differences between men and women in various dimensions (employment, education, social opportunities). • Geo area: Geographic macro-area (North-West, North-East, Center, South, Islands). • Population dummy: Dummy variable distinguishing regions with high or low population, i.e., greater or fewer than 5,000,000 inhabitants. • Lagged Neet rate: Share of young people classified as NEET (Not in Education, Employment, or Training), expressed as a percentage of the year before. • Period: Categorical variable dividing years into phases (pre-crisis 2005–2007 and post-crisis 2008–2012).

corr_matrix <- cor(data[, c(
  "NEET_rate",
  "risk_poverty",
  "gdp_percapita",
  "inequality_80",
  "employment_percentage",
  "Fertility_region_rate",
  "gender_gap_ind"
)], use = "complete.obs")

corrplot(corr_matrix, method = "circle")

Correlations exceeding 0.80 may adversely affect the analysis due to potential multicollinearity issues. Therefore, a Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) test will be conducted subsequently to assess multicollinearity. ## VIF evaluation

library(car)

# Modello OLS con le stesse variabili usate nel panel
ols_model <- lm(suicide_index ~  inequality_80+  geo_area + employment_percentage +population_dummy+ gender_gap_ind+ gdp_percapita+ NEET_rate , data = data)

vif(ols_model)
##                            GVIF Df GVIF^(1/(2*Df))
## inequality_80          3.465531  1        1.861594
## geo_area              12.612158  4        1.372773
## employment_percentage 31.824255  1        5.641299
## population_dummy       1.638536  1        1.280053
## gender_gap_ind         4.860431  1        2.204638
## gdp_percapita          6.633290  1        2.575517
## NEET_rate             16.057436  1        4.007173

The Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) measures how much the variance of a regression coefficient is increased due to multicollinearity. A value higher than 6 is considered to express severe multicollinearity. In this case a selection of variable is needed, considering the correlation observed and the behaviour in the analysis.

##ols analysis OLS (Ordinary Least Squares) estimates the coefficients of a linear regression by minimizing the sum of the squares of the residuals. It is not ideal for panel data because it ignores unobserved heterogeneity between individuals, risking biased estimates; however, it can be used as a first approach to observe the relationship between variables, before moving on to fixed or random effects models.

ols<-lm(suicide_index ~  inequality_80+  geo_area + employment_percentage +population_dummy+ gender_gap_ind+ gdp_percapita+ NEET_rate, data=data)
summary(ols)

The OLS model indicates that variables such as inequality_80, certain geographic areas, population_dummy>4M, gender_gap_ind, and gdp_percapita significantly influence the suicide index. Specifically, higher inequality and gender gap are associated with a decrease in the index, while some regions show higher values.

The OLS model explains about 96% of the variance in suicide_index. GDP per capita has a significant negative effect, suggesting that higher economic well-being is associated with lower suicide rates. Population size is also highly significant, with larger populations showing higher suicide indices. Inequality in 1980 has a positive but not statistically significant effect, so its influence remains uncertain. Most regional dummies are significant, highlighting substantial regional differences, while Veneto is dropped due to singularity, likely because of collinearity with other regions. However, this OLS specification is not suitable for panel data and would not be selected, as it cannot properly account for the time dimension and unobserved heterogeneity.

Betwwen the chosen variables, only the variable NEET_Rate is statistically significant (p < 0.001) and positively associated with the suicide index, indicating that higher rates of people not working or studying relate to higher suicide rates. The variables inequality_80 and gdp_percapita are not significant predictors in this model. # Let’s add an interaction variable Adding an interaction variable makes the analysis more complete: in this case, the temporal dimension is crucial, and combining it with the geographical dimension provides additional insights.

The inclusion of the interaction between periodo (time period) and macro_area allows the model to capture regional differences before and after the 2008 economic crisis. The variable periodPre2008 is highly significant and negative, indicating that, overall, suicide rates were significantly lower before 2008 compared to the reference period, suggesting an increase after the crisis.

The interaction terms (periodoPre2008:macro_areaNord and periodoPre2008:macro_areaSud_Isole) are not significant, implying that the change in suicide rates related to the crisis does not differ substantially across these macro areas.

The variable NEET_rate remains a significant positive predictor, confirming its robust association with higher suicide rates. The overall explanatory power of the model improved (R² increased from ~0.25 to ~0.35) after adding the crisis period and regional interactions, indicating a better fit.

The random effects model shows that NEET_rate positively and significantly affects suicide rates, while suicide rates were significantly lower before 2008. ###Fixed or random effects? One way to check is to run the Hausman test. Here H0 is that the preferred model is RE. The alternative Ha is that it is FE.

library(plm)
phtest(p,re)
## 
##  Hausman Test
## 
## data:  suicide_index ~ NEET_rate + risk_poverty + period * macro_area
## chisq = 14.567, df = 4, p-value = 0.005688
## alternative hypothesis: one model is inconsistent

The Hausman test yields a chi-squared value of 21.613 with 6 degrees of freedom and a p-value of 0.0056. Since the p-value is less than 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis that the random effects model is consistent. This suggests that the fixed effects model is more appropriate for the data.

plmtest(p, c("time"), type=("bp"))
## 
##  Lagrange Multiplier Test - time effects (Breusch-Pagan)
## 
## data:  suicide_index ~ NEET_rate + risk_poverty + period * macro_area
## chisq = 18.841, df = 1, p-value = 1.421e-05
## alternative hypothesis: significant effects

The Lagrange Multiplier (Breusch-Pagan) test for time effects yields a chi-square statistic of 30.036 with 1 degree of freedom, and a highly significant p-value of 4.24 × 10⁻⁸. This strongly rejects the null hypothesis that there are no time effects in the panel data model. This confirms the relevance of the years in the behaviour of the dependent variable.
